1
00:00:01,001 --> 00:00:02,961
This is an exciting day.

2
00:00:03,044 --> 00:00:05,630
We are going to tackle
the trolley problem.

3
00:00:05,714 --> 00:00:07,882
Is this a game?
I go first. I call blue.

4
00:00:07,966 --> 00:00:10,635
There's no... No, this is... No.

5
00:00:10,719 --> 00:00:13,221
This is a thought experiment

6
00:00:13,304 --> 00:00:17,851
first introduced by British philosopher
Philippa Foot in 1967.

7
00:00:17,934 --> 00:00:21,896
You are driving a trolley
when the brakes fail.

8
00:00:21,980 --> 00:00:27,402
And on the track ahead of you
are five workmen you will run over.

9
00:00:27,485 --> 00:00:31,865
Now, you can steer to another track,
but on that track

10
00:00:31,948 --> 00:00:34,743
is one person you'd kill
instead of the five.

11
00:00:34,826 --> 00:00:36,369
What do you do?

12
00:00:36,453 --> 00:00:37,871
Do we know anything about the people?

13
00:00:37,954 --> 00:00:42,500
Is one of them an ex-boyfriend
or that snooty girl from Rite Aid

14
00:00:42,584 --> 00:00:44,961
who was always silently judging
my purchases?

15
00:00:45,044 --> 00:00:47,422
It's like, "Yeah, chicky!
A Baby Ruth and birth control,

16
00:00:47,505 --> 00:00:49,340
I see the irony. Keep a-swiping!"

17
00:00:49,424 --> 00:00:51,384
You don't know any of the workers.

18
00:00:51,468 --> 00:00:55,055
That's easy. I switch tracks.
Kill one person instead of five.

19
00:00:55,138 --> 00:00:59,017
This is hard. The only trolley I've been
on is James Franco's ironic trolley.

20
00:00:59,100 --> 00:01:01,186
It travels backwards
from his penguin grotto

21
00:01:01,269 --> 00:01:03,688
to his garage of adult tricycles.

22
00:01:04,564 --> 00:01:06,149
Um... kill one and save five.

23
00:01:06,232 --> 00:01:08,568
Good! But there's many other versions.

24
00:01:08,651 --> 00:01:12,489
What if you knew one of the people?
Does that change the equation?

25
00:01:12,572 --> 00:01:15,075
What if you're not the driver,
you're just a bystander?

26
00:01:15,158 --> 00:01:17,494
Or let's throw the trolley out altogether.

27
00:01:17,577 --> 00:01:21,956
Let's say you're a doctor
and you can save five patients.

28
00:01:22,040 --> 00:01:27,587
But you have to kill one healthy person
and use his organs to do it.

29
00:01:27,670 --> 00:01:30,298
-But that's not the same thing.
-Why not?

30
00:01:30,381 --> 00:01:34,803
It's still choosing to kill one person
to save five, isn't it?

31
00:01:34,886 --> 00:01:38,348
Michael. You've been quiet.
What do you think about this?

32
00:01:38,431 --> 00:01:41,559
Well, obviously the dilemma is clear.

33
00:01:41,643 --> 00:01:44,229
How do you kill all six people?

34
00:01:44,312 --> 00:01:46,815
I would dangle a sharp blade
out the window

35
00:01:46,898 --> 00:01:49,609
to slice the neck of the guy
on the other track

36
00:01:49,692 --> 00:01:52,403
as we smoosh our five main guys.

37
00:01:54,864 --> 00:01:58,576
-I did the thing again, didn't I?
-Yeah. Ten more, buddy.

38
00:01:58,660 --> 00:02:02,497
People. Good. People...
Why is that so hard to remember?

39
00:02:02,580 --> 00:02:04,791
People... What is it?

40
00:02:04,874 --> 00:02:05,708
-Good.
-Good.

41
00:02:05,792 --> 00:02:10,672
